    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-04-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-04-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="221"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d221">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296 Bank for International
                    Settlements/86</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moffat</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-04-29">April 29,
                            1930</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 873</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to your despatch No. 1336 dated
                    March 5, 1930, there is enclosed a copy of an instruction of this date to the
                    American Consul at Basel regarding the Bank for International Settlements.<note
                        n="34" xml:id="d221fn34">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra.</hi>
                    </note> The Legation should exercise a general supervision over the Consulate’s
                    execution of this instruction, carefully reviewing the Consulate’s reports and
                    making to the Consul such suggestions as may seem appropriate.</p>
                <p>It is presumed that the American members of the Board of Directors of the Bank
                    will report primarily to the American banking group interested in the
                    establishment of the Bank and will not have occasion to request the assistance
                    of the Legation in their capacity as Directors or officers of the Bank. They
                    should be granted the customary courtesies accorded to all distinguished
                    Americans. Any request from them for any special facilities over and above such
                    courtesies should be carefully considered in each case and not treated as a
                    matter of routine.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. P. Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
